        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=63795&amp;TOPIC_ID=7564&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=DPS+and+the+myth+that+necros+are+not+good+at+it&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         <BR>Self DoT stacking is a bad idea. With the 30 debuff slot limit you've moved closer to anything over one necromancer being incredibly limited. Heck, even more so than before.</P><P>However the essence I like. One possibility might be like Diablo's poison system. The system is overly convoluted, but effectively stacking DoT's extends the rate of damage and duration of the DoT on the foe. So 20 necro's casting `fast' DoT's would extend the duration (which is efficiency) a bit and the potency (which is DPS) a lot. Then you could have `slow' DoT's which work the other way. I was actually hoping they'd fix DoT stacking this way rather than the kludge they used.</P><P>It would even be nice if stacking was stronger than the sum of the individual DoT's. That way 1 wizard might be able to outdamage a necro, as is currently the case. But 3 necro's casting a single stacking DoT might do more damage than three wizards. All of a sudden having multiple necromancers becomes very desirable, as opposed to the current dilution as more necro's are added.</P><P></P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
