		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=4962"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=4962')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=63799&amp;TOPIC_ID=7564&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=DPS+and+the+myth+that+necros+are+not+good+at+it&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Start a mage or wizard? No way in hell.. necro all the way.. <BR>I do think, however, that our DoT spells need some loving because:</P><P>  DoT stacking is not going to be the end-all cure for necros doing damage on a raid... the 30 buff limit helps by simply un-gimping necros number 2 and 3 on the raid and helps them reach their max potential DPS. It won't make necros any more desireable for raids. One problem is that DoTs in their current incarnation have too many disadvantages when compared to nukes..</P><P> The fact that you cannot stack multiple Pyres yourself means you are forced to use lesser DoTs if you wish to apply mana efficient damage spells (i.e. Not lifetap nukes which are inefficent).  This is a disadvantage; casting NukeX doesn't force the nuker to have to switch to a lesser spell to follow it up if he wishes to use a good ratio spell. He can follow it up with his good spell as soon as the spell gem refreshes.</P><P>  Even with the 30 slot limit and DoT stacking, there is still going to be the annoyance of deciding who is casting what DoT, there is (and will be) the possibility that the DoTs could fill up the slots, and prevent an essential debuff or slow. Many classes have DoTs, debuffs, and procs that will take up space, not just necros. There is still a limit to how many DoTs will fit on the mob. These are disadvantages. Nukers don't have to worry about this.</P><P>  DoTs do their damage over time. Meaning, that golem with 2000hp remaining that I just cast Funeral Pyre on is still swinging at me.. I am going to have to spend mana to keep it off me, either by fearing it, rooting, or kiting it. Any mana used to keep the mob off of my necro(by rooting/fearing) or mana regen lost by having to kite the mob around (i.e. not medding) should be factored into those Damage/mana calcuations IMO. The HP the mob regenned over this time should also be factored into the calculations..Yet another  disadvantage. That golem gets nuked by garrisons for its remaining 2k HP and it falls dead. The nuker can sit down and med in peace.</P><P> Non-lifetap DoTs like splurt and the ignite line are hard to resist, but there are lots of fire and magic immune mobs in the game.. In that situation the rest of our DoTs are easy to resist, and they are much higher aggro, and inefficient. If you've ever fought in Akheva you know how necro DoTs are resisted. Aside from ignite spells, everything else bounces off with resists around 80-90.   Nukes, however, seem to penetrate resists much better. </P><P> Nukes are simply too close to DoT efficiency now, or DoTs are not efficient enough to outweigh their disadvantages (especially in the raid setting) depending on how you look at it. DoTs need to do more damage, period. Make DoTs *worth* the 9 to 18 ticks and the stacking issues.</P><P> Just my opinion. </P><P><BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=34033" target="_blank">http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=34033</a><a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
